# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] In the subsequent party executive meeting on 29 October 2018, both the CDU's General Secretary Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer and the Federal Minister of Health Jens Spahn announced their candidacy in the election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] This was followed by Merkel's former arch-rival Friedrich Merz, who announced his bid and his return to politics on 30 October 2018.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] Spahn was eliminated after the first round, and Kramp-Karrenbauer subsequently won close-run second round of voting by 18 votes.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] To be able to run as candidate for CDU leader, a person needs to be endorsed by a subdivision of the party (either the federal executive board or a state, district or local association) or the proposal by a delegate during the party convention.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] The following people ran in the leadership election, having fulfilled the criteria to become a candidate in the convention.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] The following CDU politicians announced their intention to run for CDU leadership, but did not receive an endorsement by either a subdivision or a delegate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] The following politicians intended to run for the office, but withdrew their candidacy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The **2018 Hessian state election** was held on 28 October 2018 to elect the members of the Landtag of Hesse.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The outgoing government was a coalition of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and The Greens led by Minister-President Volker Bouffier.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The election was held two weeks after the 2018 Bavarian state election, which saw the CSU and Social Democratic Party (SPD) suffer major losses, with third parties making major gains.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The result in Hesse was largely similar, with the CDU and SPD losing more than 20 percentage points between them, while the Greens and Alternative for Germany (AfD) gained approximately 9 points each.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP) and The Left also made gains.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] Compared to the 2013 election turnout fell by 5.9 points to 67.3%.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] Despite suffering the worst losses of any party, the CDU remained the largest party by a comfortable margin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The Greens and SPD each won 29 seats and 19.8% of the vote; the Greens moved into second place by an extremely narrow margin of just 66 votes.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The AfD, which failed to win seats in 2013, won 13.1% and 19 seats.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] By entering the Landtag in Hesse, it became the only third party present in all sixteen state parliaments.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The election was influenced by the poor condition of the federal government in the aftermath of the "asylum quarrel" in June/July and the crisis around Hans-Georg Maaßen in September.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] One day after the election, federal Chancellor Angela Merkel announced that she would not seek re-election as CDU leader at the party convention in early December, nor seek her party's nomination as Chancellor candidate for the next federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The incumbent CDU–Green government was returned with a slim majority of one seat, and was subsequently renewed.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The incumbent Hesse government coalition consisted of CDU and the Greens.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The regional election for Hesse, along with the Bavarian state election held just two weeks before, was widely seen as a test for the ruling CDU/CSU and SPD coalition of Angela Merkel's fourth federal cabinet.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the previous Landtag of Hesse.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] Despite heavy losses inflicted on the party, the CDU returned to government after negotiating a coalition agreement with the Greens, the second consecutive such arrangement between the two parties.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The two parties formed the narrowest possible majority in the Landtag, occupying 69 seats.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] As part of the agreement, the Greens increased their representation in the Cabinet, holding four of the eleven portfolios.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] The returned coalition only became possible after a recount of votes took place several weeks after the election, due to computer glitches which affected some election night results.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/2018-hessian-state-election] Following the recount, the state election commissioner announced that compared to the provisional figures, there were no significant shifts in the percentages, and the distribution of seats in the state parliament had not changed.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] The Altmark is a historical region that covers the territory of this district as well as parts of the neighbouring district of Stendal.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] In the 10th century AD, it was the eastern border province of the Holy Roman Empire; castles were built here in order to move the borders eastwards.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] The Altmark was a swampy and heavily contested region for centuries.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] In the 12th century, many swamps were drained, and the strongholds became small towns.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] In the Late Middle Ages, many towns were members of the Hanseatic League.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] Due to the Thirty Years' War the Altmark was completely devastated in the 17th century.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] It never regained its importance and remains sparsely populated to date.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] The district was established in 1994 by merging the former districts of Gardelegen, Klötze, Salzwedel and (partially) Osterburg.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] The Altmark is a plain countryside, which once was full of fens and ponds.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] Today it is mainly covered with forests and heaths.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] It is generally dry, although some swampy regions survived.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] The largest of those is the Drömling, a large wetland in the southwest, which is a nature park shared with the neighbouring Börde (district).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] The largest lake of the district is the **Arendsee** (5.54 km2); the town of Arendsee is named after this lake.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/altmarkkreis-salzwedel] Along the northern and western border runs the European Green Belt, accompanied by the Eurovelo-route EV13 *Iron Curtain Trail*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was born in Hamburg in West Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Her family moved to East Germany when she was an infant.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] A member of the communist East German Free German Youth (FDJ), Merkel obtained a doctorate in quantum chemistry in 1986 and worked as a research scientist until 1989.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She then entered politics in the wake of the Revolutions of 1989, briefly serving as deputy spokeswoman for the first democratically elected government of East Germany, led by Lothar de Maizière.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following German reunification in 1990, Merkel was elected to the Bundestag for the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As the protégée of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Merkel was appointed as Minister for Women and Youth in 1991, later becoming Minister for the Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety in 1994.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After the CDU lost the 1998 federal election, Merkel was elected general secretary of the party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She then became the party's first female leader, and the first female leader of the Opposition, two years later.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following the 2005 federal election, Merkel was elected chancellor, leading a grand coalition consisting of the CDU, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She was the first woman to be elected chancellor, and the first chancellor of reunified Germany to have been raised in the former East Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2009 federal election, the CDU obtained the largest share of the vote, and Merkel subsequently formed a coalition government with the Free Democratic Party (FDP), an alliance more favourable to the CDU than the grand coalition.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2013 federal election, the CDU won a landslide victory and formed a second grand coalition with the SPD, after the FDP lost all of its representation in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2017 federal election, Merkel led the CDU to become the largest party for the fourth time, resulting in the formation of a third grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In foreign policy, Merkel emphasised international cooperation, both in the context of the EU and NATO, and initiating the Russian reset and strengthening of Eurasian and transatlantic economic relations.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the first half of 2007, Merkel served as president of the European Council and played a central role in the negotiation of the Treaty of Lisbon and the Berlin Declaration.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's governments managed the 2008 financial crisis and the Euro area crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She negotiated the 2008 European Union stimulus plan, which focused on infrastructure spending and public investment to counteract the Great Recession.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Also in 2008, she actively blocked the access of Ukraine and Georgia in the enlargement of NATO during the 2008 Bucharest summit.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In domestic policy, Merkel's *Energiewende* programme supported the development of renewable energy sources and eventually phased out the use of nuclear power in Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Despite the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea, which prompted sanctions around the world, she initiated the construction of the controversial Nord Stream 2 pipelines to Russia and protected their construction from United States sanctions imposed in 2019.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Reforms to the *Bundeswehr*, health care reform, the 2010s European migrant crisis, and the COVID-19 pandemic were major issues during her chancellorship.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel stepped down as leader of the CDU in 2018 and did not seek a fifth term as chancellor in the 2021 federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, her legacy came under increased scrutiny both in Germany and abroad for her relatively good relations with Russia and increasing the German economy's dependence on Russia, as well as the downsizing of the *Bundeswehr* that occurred during her tenure.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She has two younger siblings, Marcus Kasner, a physicist, and Irene Kasner, an occupational therapist.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In her childhood and youth, Merkel was known among her peers by the nickname "Kasi", derived from her last name Kasner.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Her paternal grandfather, Ludwik Kasner, was a German policeman of Polish ethnicity.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After being captured in France during World War I, he joined the Blue Army and likely fought against Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] He married Merkel's grandmother Margarethe, a German from Berlin, and relocated to her hometown where he again worked in the police.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 1930, they Germanised the Polish name Kaźmierczak to Kasner.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's maternal grandparents were the Danzig politician Willi Jentzsch and Gertrud Alma (née Drange), a daughter of the city clerk of Elbing (now Elbląg, Poland) Emil Drange.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Since the mid-1990s, Merkel has publicly mentioned her Polish heritage on several occasions and described herself as a quarter Polish, but her Polish roots became better known as a result of a 2013 biography.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Religion played a key role in the Kasner family's migration from West Germany to East Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's paternal grandfather was originally Catholic but the entire family converted to Lutheranism during the childhood of her father, who later studied Lutheran theology in Heidelberg and Hamburg.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 1954, when Angela was just three months old, her father received a pastorate at the church in Quitzow (a district of Perleberg in Brandenburg), which was then in East Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The family moved to Templin and Merkel grew up in the countryside 90 km (56 mi) north of East Berlin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 1968, Merkel joined the Free German Youth (FDJ), the official communist youth movement sponsored by the ruling Marxist–Leninist Socialist Unity Party of Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Membership was nominally voluntary, but those who did not join found it difficult to gain admission to higher education.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She did not participate in the secular coming-of-age ceremony Jugendweihe, however, which was common in East Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] During this time, she participated in several compulsory courses on Marxism–Leninism, with her grades only being regarded as "sufficient".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She completed her school education with the best possible average Abitur grade of 1.0.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel continued her education at Karl Marx University, Leipzig, where she studied physics from 1973 to 1978.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] While a student, she participated in the reconstruction of the ruin of the Moritzbastei, a project students initiated to create their own club and recreation facility on campus.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Such an initiative was unprecedented in the GDR of that period, and initially resisted by the university.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] With the backing of the local leadership of the SED party, the project was allowed to proceed.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Near the end of her studies, Merkel sought an assistant professorship at an engineering school.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As a condition for getting the job, Merkel was told she would need to agree to report on her colleagues to officers of the Stasi.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel declined, using the excuse that she could not keep secrets well enough to be an effective spy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel worked and studied at the Central Institute for Physical Chemistry of the Academy of Sciences in Berlin-Adlershof from 1978 to 1990.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] At first, she and her husband squatted in Mitte.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] At the Academy of Sciences, she became a member of its FDJ secretariat.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] According to her former colleagues, she openly propagated Marxism as the secretary for "Agitation and Propaganda".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, Merkel has denied this claim and stated that she was secretary for culture, which involved activities like obtaining theatre tickets and organising talks by visiting Soviet authors.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After being awarded a doctorate (*Dr. rer. nat.*) for her thesis on quantum chemistry in 1986, she worked as a researcher and published several academic papers.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 1986, she was allowed to travel to West Germany to attend a congress.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She also participated in a multi-week Russian language course in Donetsk, in the then-Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989 served as the catalyst for Merkel's political career.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although she did not participate in the crowd celebrations the night the wall came down, one month later Merkel became involved in the growing democracy movement, joining the new party Democratic Awakening (*Demokratischer Aufbruch*, abbreviated to DA).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Party Leader Wolfgang Schnur appointed her as press spokeswoman of the party in February 1990.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, Schnur was revealed to have served as an "informal co-worker" for the Stasi just a few weeks ahead of the first (and only) multi-party election in 1990 and was later expelled from the party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As a result, the DA lost most of its electoral support, only managing to obtain four seats in the Volkskammer.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, because the DA was a member party of the Alliance for Germany, which won the election in a landslide, the DA was included in the government coalition.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was appointed deputy spokesperson of this last pre-unification government under Lothar de Maizière.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] De Maizière was impressed with the way Merkel handled journalists investigating Schnur's role in the Stasi.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In April 1990, the DA merged with the East German Christian Democratic Union, which in turn merged with its western counterpart after reunification.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the German federal election of 1990, the first to be held following reunification, Merkel successfully stood for election to the Bundestag in the parliamentary constituency of Stralsund – Nordvorpommern – Rügen in North Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She received the crucial backing of influential CDU minister and state party chairman Günther Krause.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She was re-elected from this constituency (renamed, with slightly adjusted borders, Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I in 2003) in every election until the CDU lost its direct mandate from the constituency in the 2021 federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Almost immediately following her entry into parliament, Merkel was appointed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl to serve as Minister for Women and Youth in the federal cabinet.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In November 1991, Merkel, with the support of the federal CDU, ran for the state leadership of the CDU in the state of Brandenburg, which neighbours Berlin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In June 1993, Merkel was elected leader of the CDU in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, succeeding her former mentor Günther Krause.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although Merkel had little interest in the political position as such, it has been described as instrumental in building her early political image.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] During her tenure, the government codified the right to preschool education, although the law only went into effect in 1996.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In June 1992, § 218 of the StGB, which governed abortion rights, was rewritten to allow abortions until the 12th week of pregnancy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Though she was personally opposed to abortion at the time, Merkel abstained during the vote on the bill.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The law was later overturned by the Federal Constitutional Court on the basis that there must be a general prohibition of abortion.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 1994, she was promoted to the position of Minister for the Environment and Nuclear Safety, which gave her greater political visibility and a platform on which to build her personal political career.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As one of Kohl's protégées and his youngest Cabinet Minister, she was frequently referred to by Kohl as "my girl" (*mein Mädchen*).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] During this period, she was closely mentored by Kohl.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As Minister of the Environment, Merkel was instrumental in setting up the United Nations 1995 Berlin Climate Change Conference.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She is often credited as having brought about its most notable result, the first international commitment to a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Around this time, she also first hired Beate Baumann, who would remain a close advisor to Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's performance as Minister of the Environment was criticised as "pitiful" by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After the Kohl Government was defeated at the 1998 election, Merkel was appointed Secretary-General of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The 1998 election had widespread impacts; it was the CDU's worst performance in a federal election since 1949, and it resulted in Germany's first post-war left-wing government, led by the SPD.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the wake of this defeat on the federal level, Merkel oversaw a string of CDU election victories in six out of seven state elections in 1999, breaking the long-standing SPD-Green hold on the Bundesrat.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following a party funding scandal that compromised many leading figures of the CDU – including Kohl himself and his successor as CDU Leader, Wolfgang Schäuble – Merkel criticised her former mentor publicly and advocated a fresh start for the party without him.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 10 April 2000, Merkel was elected to replace Schäuble as Chairperson of the CDU, becoming the first female leader of a German party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following Merkel's election as CDU Leader, the CDU did not obtain electoral victories in subsequent state elections.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In February 2001, her rival Friedrich Merz voiced his intention to become Gerhard Schröder's main challenger for Chancellorship in the 2002 election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's ambition to become Chancellor was well-known, but she lacked the support of the most influential members within her own party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Rival candidate and leader of the CSU Edmund Stoiber was much more popular within the party at the time.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In a private negotiation that came to be known as the Wolfratshausen Breakfast, Merkel agreed to cede the opportunity to challenge Schröder to Stoiber; in exchange, she was to become leader of the CDU/CSU faction in the Bundestag following the election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although pre-election polling had indicated that voters strongly favoured Stoiber, he went on to lose the election by a thin margin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The election campaign was dominated by the Iraq War.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] While Chancellor Schröder had made clear he would not join the war in Iraq, Merkel was in support of the war at the time, although she later claimed that she had opposed it.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After Stoiber's defeat in 2002, in addition to her role as CDU Leader, Merkel became Leader of the Opposition in the Bundestag, as had been agreed upon between her and Stoiber.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Friedrich Merz, who had held the post prior to the 2002 election, was eased out to make way for Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel supported a substantial reform agenda for Germany's economic and social system and was considered more pro-market than her own party (the CDU).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She advocated German labour law changes, specifically removing barriers to laying off employees and increasing the allowed number of work hours in a week.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She argued that existing laws made the country less competitive, because companies could not easily control labour costs when business was slow.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel argued that Germany should phase out nuclear power less quickly than the Schröder administration had planned.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel advocated a strong transatlantic partnership and German-American friendship.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the spring of 2003, defying strong public opposition, Merkel came out in favour of the 2003 invasion of Iraq, describing it as "unavoidable".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She also criticised the government's support for the accession of Turkey to the European Union, instead arguing in favour of a "privileged partnership".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 30 May 2005, Merkel won the CDU/CSU nomination to challenge Chancellor Gerhard Schröder of the SPD in the 2005 federal elections.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Her party began the campaign with a 21–point lead over the SPD in national opinion polls, although her personal popularity lagged behind that of the incumbent.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, the CDU/CSU campaign suffered when Merkel, having made economic competence central to the CDU's platform, confused gross and net income twice during a televised debate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She regained some momentum after she announced that she would appoint Paul Kirchhof, a former judge at the German Constitutional Court and leading fiscal policy expert, as Minister of Finance.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel and the CDU lost ground after Kirchhof proposed the introduction of a flat tax in Germany, again undermining the party's broad appeal on economic affairs.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] This was compounded by Merkel's proposal to increase VAT to reduce Germany's deficit and fill the gap in revenue from a flat tax.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The SPD were able to increase their support simply by pledging not to introduce flat taxes or increase VAT.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although Merkel's standing recovered after she distanced herself from Kirchhof's proposals, she remained considerably less popular than Schröder, who had been perceived as the more generally competent and trustworthy candidate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The CDU's lead was down to 9 percentage points on the eve of the election, with Merkel having a significant lead in popularity based on opinion polls.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 18 September 2005, Merkel's CDU/CSU and Schröder's SPD went head-to-head in the national elections, with the CDU/CSU winning 35.2% (CDU 27.8% / CSU 7.5%) of the second votes to the SPD's 34.2%.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The result was so close that both Schröder and Merkel initially claimed victory.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Neither the SPD–Green coalition nor the CDU/CSU and its preferred coalition partners, the Free Democratic Party, held enough seats to form a majority in the Bundestag.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] A grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and SPD would face the challenge of both parties demanding the chancellorship.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, after three weeks of negotiations, the two parties reached a deal for a grand coalition whereby Merkel would become Chancellor and the SPD would hold 8 of the 16 seats in the cabinet.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The deal was approved by both parties at party conferences on 14 November 2005.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was elected Chancellor by the majority of delegates (397 to 217) in the newly assembled Bundestag on 22 November 2005, but 51 members of the governing coalition voted against her.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Reports at the time indicated that the grand coalition would pursue a mix of policies, some of which differed from Merkel's political platform as leader of the opposition and candidate for Chancellor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The coalition's intent was to cut public spending whilst increasing VAT (from 16 to 19%), social insurance contributions and the top rate of income tax.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] When announcing the coalition agreement, Merkel stated that the main aim of her government would be to reduce unemployment, and that it was this issue on which her government would be judged.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Reform of the German healthcare system was a salient issue during the 2005 election; the previous system had been criticised as inefficient and overly bureaucratic.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After a significant period of negotiations, a deal was passed in 2006.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] While this agreement was described as having "saved the coalition government", it was also widely criticised as ineffectual.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The deal also increased the tax burden on employers and their publicly insured employees.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The 2006 round of reforms introduced the "health insurance duty", which establishes that individuals must be insured either through the public insurance system or through private insurance firms and accordingly cannot be uninsured.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The reforms also targeted preventive healthcare as a priority, particularly with regards to eldercare.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 4 October 2008, following the Irish Government's decision to guarantee all deposits in private savings accounts, a move she had strongly criticised, Merkel said there were no plans for the German Government to do the same.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The following day, Merkel stated that the government would guarantee private savings account deposits, after all.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, two days later, on 6 October 2008, it emerged that the pledge was simply a political move that would not be backed by legislation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Most other European governments eventually either raised the limits or promised to guarantee savings in full.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The German government stepped in to assist the mortgage company Hypo Real Estate with a bailout.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The deal was agreed upon on 6 October, with German banks contributing €30 billion and the Bundesbank €20 billion to an emergency credit line.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] At the time of the Greek government-debt crisis, Germany was the largest creditor of the Greek government, giving it significant negotiating power.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel is often credited as having "saved the Euro", primarily due to her coordinating role in the development of debt relief policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The austerity measures imposed on debtors such as Greece, which were a significant part of Merkel's position in the negotiations, have been criticised as overly harsh by some observers.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Critics also highlighted Germany's own debt management issues.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the course of the 2008 financial crisis, the Merkel cabinet increased the budget of the Kurzarbeit programme significantly and extended the permitted duration of such contracts from 6 months to 18 months.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although similar provisions had existed previously, the Merkel cabinet's expansion of the programme was widely praised and is credited with having saved 500,000 jobs during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's CDU was re-elected in 2009 with an increased number of seats and could form a governing coalition with the FDP.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After brief negotiations, the second Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 28 October 2009.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In early 2011, Merkel's approval ratings plummeted, resulting in heavy losses in state elections for her party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] An August 2011 poll found her coalition had only 36% support compared to a rival potential coalition's 51%.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Notwithstanding the effects of the 2008 financial crisis, unemployment sank below 3 million unemployed people in 2011.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following increased debate on the subject in the summer of 2010, the German government announced plans to abolish conscription in Germany, making the *Bundeswehr* a volunteer military, in November 2010.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The decision was finalised in December that year, and conscription was suspended on 1 July 2011.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although somewhat popular at the time, the decision has later come under scrutiny, particularly following to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] It has also been criticised in conjunction with Germany's financial commitments to NATO.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2023, 61% of Germans said that they were in favour of reestablishing conscription.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Responding to a budget deficit of €11 billion in the public healthcare system in 2009, the Merkel government passed widely unpopular healthcare reforms in 2010.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The changes reduced healthcare spending in certain areas and increased employer and employee contributions to 15.5% of gross wages.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The reforms also established that future contribution increases would only affect the contributions by employers, which was criticised by opposition parties and trade unions.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the election of September 2013, Merkel won one of the most decisive victories in German history, achieving the best result for the CDU/CSU since reunification and coming within five seats of the first absolute majority in the Bundestag since 1957.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, their preferred coalition partner, the FDP, failed to enter parliament for the first time since 1949, being below the minimum of 5% of second votes required to enter parliament.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The CDU/CSU turned to the SPD to form the third grand coalition in postwar German history and the second under Merkel's leadership.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The third Cabinet of Angela Merkel was sworn in on 17 December 2013.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel scored well in opinion polls on her handling of the recent euro crisis (69% rated her performance as good rather than poor), and her approval rating reached an all-time high of 77% in February 2012 and again in July 2014.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Throughout the course of the European migrant crisis, Merkel encouraged cooperation between EU member states, urging that Europe needs to act "as a whole".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In late August 2015, at the height of the crisis, Merkel's government suspended the Dublin Regulation, which stipulated that asylum seekers must seek asylum in the first EU country they arrive in.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel announced that Germany would also process asylum applications from Syrian refugees if they had come to Germany through other EU countries.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] That year, nearly 1.1 million asylum seekers entered Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel coined the phrase *Wir schaffen das* (literally 'We can do this') around this time.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Junior coalition partner and Vice Chancellor Sigmar Gabriel said that Germany could take in 500,000 refugees annually for the next several years.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] German opposition to the government's admission of the new wave of migrants was strong and coupled with a rise in anti-immigration protests.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel insisted that Germany had the economic strength to cope with the influx of migrants and reiterated that there is no legal maximum limit on the number of migrants Germany can take.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2015, enthusiastic crowds across the country welcomed arriving refugees and migrants.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Horst Seehofer, leader of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU)—the sister party of Merkel's Christian Democratic Union—and then-Bavarian Minister President, attacked Merkel's policies.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] He argued for a punitive reduction in EU funding for member countries that rejected mandatory refugee quotas.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Meanwhile, Yasmin Fahimi, secretary-general of the Social Democratic Party (SPD), the junior partner of the ruling coalition, praised Merkel's policy allowing migrants in Hungary to enter Germany as "a strong signal of humanity to show that Europe's values are valid also in difficult times".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's approval rating dropped to 54% in October 2015, the lowest it had been since 2011.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In November 2015, there were talks inside the governing coalition to stop family unification for migrants for two years and to establish "Transit Zones" on the border.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Additionally, there were plans to provide housing to migrants with a low likelihood of getting approved for asylum until the processing of their application.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] This led to increased tensions between the CSU, who were generally in favour of these measures and threatened to leave the coalition without them, and the SPD, who opposed them; Merkel agreed to the measures.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The November 2015 Paris attacks prompted a reevaluation of the German government's stance on EU migration policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] While she did not directly limit the number of immigrants, Merkel tightened asylum policy in Germany, for example through more thorough vetting of migrants with respect to internal safety and security.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In August 2016, following the Würzburg train attack in Germany and various other Islamist terror attacks in Europe, Merkel's approval rating dropped to 47%.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Half of Germans did not want her to serve a fourth term in office, with only 42% in favour of another term in office.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In a poll from October that year, her approval rating was found to have risen again; 54% of Germans were found to be satisfied with the work of Merkel as Chancellor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] According to another poll taken in November 2016, 59% were to found to be in favour of a renewed Chancellorship candidature in 2017.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] According to a poll carried out shortly after the 2016 Berlin truck attack, 56% of Germans named Merkel as a political leader they trusted to solve their country's problems.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In October 2016, Merkel travelled to Mali and Niger.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The diplomatic visit took place to discuss how their governments could improve conditions which caused people to flee those countries and how illegal migration through and from these countries could be reduced.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The migrant crisis spurred right-wing electoral preferences across Germany with the Alternative for Germany (AfD) gaining 12% of the vote in the 2017 German federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] These developments prompted debates over the reasons for increased right-wing populism in Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Some researchers have argued that increased right-wing preferences are a result of the European migrant crisis, particularly the increasingly common perception that refugees constitute an ethnic and cultural threat to Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Some observers have described Merkel's policymaking with respect to the migrant crisis as a success.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2022, the United Nations' High Commissioner for Refugees granted Merkel the Nansen Award for her "courage and compassion" during the crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, Merkel has also faced significant criticism, particularly with regards to her policymaking early in the crisis, which some critics describe as hypocritically unilateral.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2017 federal election, Merkel led her party to victory for the fourth time.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, both the CDU/CSU and the SPD received a significantly lower proportion of the vote than they did in 2013, and the CDU/CSU subsequently attempted to form a coalition with the FDP and Greens.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The SPD announced that they would go into the Opposition, both due to their loss of popular support and because the idea of another grand coalition was widely unpopular at the time.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The FDP eventually withdrew from negotiations with the CDU/CSU, leading to a stalemate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The German President Frank-Walter Steinmeier subsequently appealed successfully to the SPD to change their hard stance against coalition with the CDU/CSU, and the SPD agreed to a third grand coalition with the CDU/CSU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The negotiations leading up to this agreement were the longest in German post-war history, lasting almost six months.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] A YouGov survey published in late December 2017 found that just 36% of all respondents wanted Merkel to stay at the helm until 2021, while half of those surveyed voters called for a change at the top before the end of the legislature.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The Fourth Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 14 March 2018.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As part of the newly formed government, the CSU's Horst Seehofer took over the role of Interior Minister.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Seehofer announced that he had a "master plan for faster asylum procedures, and more consistent deportations." Under Seehofer's plan, Germany would immediately reject prospective immigrants who had already been deported or were subject to an entry ban.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Additionally, the police would be instructed to turn away all applicants who had previously registered elsewhere in the EU, no matter if these countries agreed to take them back.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel feared that unilaterally sending migrants back to neighbouring countries without seeking a multilateral European agreement could endanger the stability of the European Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In June 2018, Seehofer issued an ultimatum to Merkel; as Interior Minister, he could unilaterally implement the policy without her support.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although he eventually agreed to cooperate with Merkel while she negotiated with other EU member countries, he went on to reject the EU agreement that she obtained.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 1 July 2018, during a meeting with party leadership, Seehofer declared his intention to resign from his position in protest.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] During the night of 2 July 2018, Seehofer and Merkel announced they had settled their differences and agreed to instead accept a compromise of tighter border control.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] As a result of the agreement, Seehofer agreed to not resign, and to negotiate bilateral agreements with the specific countries himself.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Seehofer received some criticism for his stance in the crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the initial phases of the pandemic, Germany established a crisis team to manage Germany's containment policy and pandemic response.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In late February 2020, referring to this crisis team, Merkel recommended an approach characterised by moderation and an avoidance of extreme or universal measures (*Maß und Mitte*).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The speech was well-received both nationally and internationally, receiving widespread attention and an award for "speech of the year".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 6 April 2020, Merkel stated: "In my view ... the European Union is facing the biggest test since its foundation and member states must show greater solidarity so that the bloc can emerge stronger from the economic crisis unleashed by the pandemic".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has won international plaudits for her handling of the pandemic in Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Later that month, Merkel was praised for her accessible explanation of the basic reproduction number, which had been an important metric in the German government's pandemic response.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel opposed mandatory vaccinations, instead stressing scientific literacy and education.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] During the German presidency of the European Council, Merkel spearheaded negotiations for the Next Generation EU reconstruction package.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 29 October 2018, Merkel announced that she would not seek reelection as leader of CDU at their party conference in December 2018, but intended to remain as chancellor until the 2021 German federal election was held.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She stated that she did not plan to seek any political office after this.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The resignations followed October setbacks for the CSU in the Bavarian state election and for the CDU in the Hessian state election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In August 2019, Merkel hinted that she might return to academia at the end of her term in 2021.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She decided not to suggest any person as her successor as leader of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, political observers had long considered Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer as Merkel's protégé groomed for succession.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] This view was confirmed when Kramp-Karrenbauer – widely seen as the chancellor's favourite for the post – was voted to succeed Merkel as leader of the CDU in December 2018.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Kramp-Karrenbauer's elevation to Defence Minister after Ursula von der Leyen's departure to become president of the European Commission also boosted her standing as Merkel's most likely candidate for succession.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2019, media outlets speculated that Kramp-Karrenbauer might take over Merkel's position as Chancellor sooner than planned if the current governing coalition proved unsustainable.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The possibility was neither confirmed nor denied by the party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In February 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer announced that she would resign as party leader of the CDU in the summer, after party members in Thuringia defied official party lines and voted with Alternative for Germany to support an FDP candidate for minister-president.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Kramp-Karrenbauer was succeeded by Armin Laschet at the 2021 CDU leadership election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2021 federal election, the SPD won the most votes.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] This necessitated long negotiations among the various parties to form a government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 23 November 2021, a new coalition was announced, with Olaf Scholz nominated to succeed Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel continued to serve as chancellor until 8 December 2021, when Scholz was sworn in.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The constituency she had held since its establishment in the German reunification was won by Anna Kassautzki (SPD).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 31 January 2022, less than two months after she left office, her long-time rival Friedrich Merz, whom she beat in 2002 to become leader of the opposition, took over as leader of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In April that year, a spokesperson for Merkel stated that she "stood by her position at the NATO summit in Bucharest in 2008", when she had opposed Ukraine's membership in the North Atlantic Alliance, a decision that had come under increased scrutiny.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 1 June 2022, Merkel made her first semi-public comments about political affairs since leaving office, at a retirement party for Reiner Hoffmann, the president of the German Trade Union Confederation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 7 June 2022, Merkel made her first public comments.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She also said that by the end of her chancellorship in September 2021, it had been clear that Putin was moving in the direction of conflict and that he was finished with the Normandy Format talks.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following her retirement, Merkel wrote a memoir called *Freedom* (Freiheit), with her longtime assistant and adviser, Beate Baumann.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] It was released on 26 November 2024 with the title *Freedom: Memories 1954–2021*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The book was published in 30 languages and consists of 736 pages.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In January 2025, Merkel criticised Friedrich Merz for introducing a non-binding resolution supporting restrictions on immigration that passed in the Bundestag with the help of the AfD.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Following the CDU/CSU's victory in the 2025 German federal election, Merkel attended the first round of voting in the Bundestag to elect Merz as Chancellor on 6 May 2025.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In October 2025 Merkel gave a long interview to Hungarian media in which she made a number of controversial statements, partly reverting her previous position.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She said that in 2021 she attempted to build a "new diplomatic format" to speak to Putin "as EU", but this was "opposed by Poland and Baltic states" and then she left her position shortly before the war broke out in 2022, thus indirectly blaming the countries for the war.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She also said that "coronavirus pandemic that played a decisive role in Russia’s invasion of Ukraine" because Putin was afraid of the virus and didn't want to talk face to face.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Anyone who doesn't accept that is in the wrong place here." She continued to say that immigrants should integrate and adopt Germany's culture and values.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] This added to a growing debate within Germany on the acceptable levels and mechanisms of immigration, its effects on Germany, and the degree to which Muslim immigrants had integrated into German society.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel is in favour of a "mandatory solidarity mechanism" for relocation of asylum-seekers from Italy and Greece to other EU member states as part of the long-term solution to Europe's migrant crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's foreign policy has focused on strengthening European cooperation and international trade agreements.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She and her governments have been closely associated with the change through trade (*Wandel durch Handel*) policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] For this, she has come under criticism, especially after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has been widely described as the *de facto* leader of the European Union throughout her tenure as Chancellor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2015, with the absence of Stephen Harper, Merkel became the only leader to have attended every G20 meeting since the first in 2008, having been present at a record fifteen summits as of 2021.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She hosted the twelfth meeting at the 2017 G20 Hamburg summit.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel favors the Association Agreement between Ukraine and the European Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In December 2012, she stated that its implementation depends on reforms in Ukraine.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel expressed support for Israel's right to self-defence in the context of the 2014 Israel–Gaza conflict.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on 9 July to condemn "without reservation rocket fire on Israel".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] On 20 June 2018, which was World Refugee Day, Merkel said that there had been "no moral or political justification" for the post-war expulsion of ethnic Germans from Central and Eastern European countries.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] At the World Economic Forum in Davos, 2013, Merkel said that Europe had only 7% of the global population and produced only 25% of the global GDP, but that it accounted for almost 50% of global social expenditure.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] She went on to say that Europe could only maintain its prosperity by being innovative and measuring itself against the best.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] After this, the comparison became a central element in major speeches.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The *Financial Times* commented: "Although Ms Merkel stopped short of suggesting that a ceiling on social spending might be one yardstick for measuring competitiveness, she hinted as much in the light of soaring social spending in the face of an ageing population.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has been credited as a key part of 2007 G8 negotiations that led to a significantly more ambitious renewable energy transition commitment than had been anticipated.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2010, the coalition government published a long-term plan for sustainable development of the electrical grid until 2050; efforts to transition to sustainable and otherwise preferable sources of energy have been termed Energy Transition (*Energiewende*).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although the initial plan was criticised for lifetime extensions of nuclear power plants, it was amended following the Fukushima nuclear disaster, and the last nuclear power plants in Germany were shut down in April 2023.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The plan also aimed at a 40% reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 2020, a goal that was initially achieved largely due to reductions in demand during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] However, emissions increased to a level above the target in 2022.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In preparation for the 2015 Paris Climate Change Conference, Merkel announced that Germany would significantly increase its contributions to international climate aid and financing by 2020.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2016, some observers criticised Merkel's lack of action with regards to climate change that year.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2017, Merkel criticised the Trump administration's decision to withdraw from the 2015 Paris Agreement and reaffirmed the commitment of the remaining G20 members to the treaty.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In early 2019, a governmental commission appointed by the coalition government approved a plan to phase out coal power plants by 2038, allocating a budget of €40 billion to the plan.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2019, the Merkel government announced a set of climate change mitigation policies with a total budget of €54 billion.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Although described as a "new beginning for Germany's climate policy" by then-minister of the environment Svenja Schulze, the package was widely criticised; environmental protection groups have labelled it insufficient, and opposition parties have argued that it is ineffective.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] Prominent climate scientists have called it "a failure of the political system" and "ridiculous".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2009, Merkel announced plans to take on additional government debt in order to stimulate economic growth, arguing that this should take priority over other fiscal concerns.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] The Merkel government's tax policy at the time was widely criticised, mostly for taking on additional debt instead of increasing tax rates at high levels of income.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2010, Merkel expressed support for a global financial transaction tax, but was ultimately unsuccessful in international negotiations on the matter.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p01] In 2019, Merkel argued for the importance of a balanced government budget, rejecting calls for additional investment to stimulate growth.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's chancellorship attracted criticism across several policy areas, including her handling of Islam and public integration debates, the eurozone crisis, migration, Turkey, China, Russia, energy policy and the wider development of Euroscepticism in Europe.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for attending the 2010 M100 Media Award ceremony at which Danish cartoonist Kurt Westergaard was honoured.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Westergaard had drawn cartoons central to the Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Although Merkel defended her attendance as a statement in favour of press freedom, critics argued that her presence gave political legitimacy to material widely viewed by Muslims as offensive.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The Central Council of Muslims in Germany criticised the decision, saying that Westergaard had insulted the Prophet Muhammad and that the award came at a highly charged time in Germany's debate over Islam and immigration.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Politicians from Die Linke and the Greens also criticised Merkel's participation, while commentators noted the sensitivity of a German chancellor and leader of the Christian Democratic Union personally honouring the cartoonist during a period of intense debate over Muslim integration.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised from within her own political camp after stating in 2015 that "Islam is part of Germany", a formulation previously associated with former German president Christian Wulff.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Volker Kauder, then parliamentary group leader of the CDU/CSU, rejected the statement, saying that Muslims belonged to Germany but Islam did not.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Several of Merkel's public formulations became targets of criticism and ridicule.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Her frequent use of the term *alternativlos* to describe measures taken during the European sovereign-debt crisis was criticised as politically undemocratic, since it implied that alternatives to her policies were unnecessary or illegitimate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The term was named Germany's Un-word of the Year in 2010.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Her 2013 statement that the internet was *Neuland* also prompted widespread online mockery and criticism.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's handling of the European sovereign-debt crisis was one of the most criticised aspects of her chancellorship.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her government turned the eurozone crisis into a test of fiscal discipline and debtor-country compliance, rather than treating it as a structural crisis of the monetary union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Commentators and politicians in several EU member states accused Berlin of imposing excessive austerity on countries such as Greece, Spain and Portugal, deepening social hardship and fuelling anti-EU sentiment.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel also faced criticism from within her own political tradition.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In July 2011, *Der Spiegel* reported that former chancellor Helmut Kohl, Merkel's former mentor and a central figure in German reunification and European integration, had criticised her handling of the eurozone crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism intensified during the 2015 Greek bailout negotiations, after the election of the Syriza-led government in January 2015.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel and the German government were identified with the creditor side's insistence on prior reforms, fiscal consolidation, conditionality and privatisation before the release of further funds.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In July 2015, after Greece missed a repayment to the International Monetary Fund, its second bailout expired and Greek voters rejected the creditors' proposal in a referendum, Merkel and other eurozone leaders pressed Greece to accept a third bailout under stricter terms.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics accused Merkel and finance minister Wolfgang Schäuble of using the threat of *Grexit* as leverage and of forcing Greece to surrender fiscal and economic sovereignty in order to remain in the eurozone.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Criticism also focused on the requirement for Greece to privatise or transfer control of state assets.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents argued that the bailout framework went beyond fiscal adjustment by requiring the disposal of strategic Greek public assets, thereby weakening Greek economic sovereignty.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The 14 Greek regional airports concession became one of the most symbolic examples.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] A preliminary deal with a consortium led by Germany's Fraport AG had been agreed in 2014, but was reviewed after the Syriza government came to power.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In August 2015, shortly after the third bailout agreement, Greece confirmed that it would proceed with the concession as part of the latest bailout with its lenders.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The agreement was signed in December 2015 and Fraport Greece began operating the airports in April 2017 under a long-term concession.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] For critics in Greece and southern Europe, the Fraport concession became emblematic of a wider creditor-driven programme in which public assets were transferred to foreign operators while Greek society absorbed the costs of austerity.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The same criticism was applied to other privatisations, including the sale of a majority stake in the Port of Piraeus to China's COSCO, the sale of railway operator TRAINOSE to Italy's Ferrovie dello Stato Italiane and the sale of a further stake in OTE to Germany's Deutsche Telekom.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Scholars and commentators have linked the eurozone crisis and the subsequent austerity policies to the rise of Euroscepticism and radical parties across Europe.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In this criticism, Merkel's crisis management is presented not only as an economic policy failure, but also as a political factor that weakened trust in EU institutions and mainstream parties in several member states.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's response to the European migrant crisis of 2015 was heavily criticised by opponents in Germany and abroad.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that the size and speed of the inflow exposed weaknesses in Germany's administrative capacity and contributed to a public backlash against Merkel's government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Analysts have linked this backlash to the rise of the Alternative for Germany and to broader changes in the German party system.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's refugee policy also became a recurring target in far-right and Eurosceptic discourse, where it was portrayed as evidence of elite detachment from public concerns over borders, identity and security.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] More broadly, the eurozone crisis and the refugee crisis have been identified in academic literature as key drivers of rising Euroscepticism and support for radical parties across Europe in the 2010s.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics of Merkel argue that her role in both crises made her one of the central political figures associated with this wider backlash.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for her pragmatic relationship with Turkish president Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, particularly after the 2015 refugee crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her reliance on Turkey to reduce irregular migration into the European Union gave Erdoğan political leverage over Germany and the EU at a time when his government was facing increasing criticism over human rights, press freedom and the rule of law.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents argued that the arrangement prioritised border control over refugee protection and made the EU dependent on cooperation with an increasingly authoritarian Turkish government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel faced further criticism during the Böhmermann affair in April 2016, when her government allowed prosecutors to consider a case against German comedian Jan Böhmermann after Erdoğan complained about a satirical poem.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics accused Merkel of failing to defend freedom of expression and of accommodating Erdoğan.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] A Reuters-reported poll found that two thirds of Germans opposed her decision to allow the prosecution to proceed.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised over Germany's approach to Turkish pressure on Greece and Cyprus.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] During the 2020 Greek–Turkish border crisis, Erdoğan opened Turkey's border with Europe and thousands of migrants attempted to enter Greece.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel criticised Erdoğan for using refugees to express political grievances with the EU, but critics argued that Germany's wider policy remained constrained by its dependence on Turkish cooperation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Similar criticism arose during the Eastern Mediterranean crisis, when Turkey carried out energy exploration and maritime claims disputed by Greece and Cyprus.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that Germany under Merkel prioritised mediation and de-escalation over firm solidarity with Greece and Cyprus.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Academic analysis of the crisis noted that Germany avoided full identification with the positions of Cyprus and Greece, objected to a sanctions-based agenda against Turkey and sought to maintain open diplomatic channels with Ankara.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for failing to take a tougher line towards the People's Republic of China.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her governments prioritised German commercial interests and export access over stronger public criticism of Beijing on human rights, Hong Kong and strategic dependency.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Her approach was frequently characterised by opponents as overly cautious and too focused on trade.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism intensified during the Hong Kong protests and wider European debates over relations with China.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's China policy was criticised as an example of Germany's reluctance to confront authoritarian governments when major economic interests were involved.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Some commentators later described China as one of the major weaknesses of her foreign-policy legacy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Merkel faced renewed criticism over her Russia policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that she had underestimated Vladimir Putin's ambitions, relied too heavily on diplomacy and détente, and failed to prepare Germany and Europe for a more confrontational Russian policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Her governments were criticised for allowing Germany to become heavily dependent on Russian energy, including through Nord Stream 1 and Nord Stream 2.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised over the condition of the Bundeswehr during and after her chancellorship.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that Germany's armed forces had been neglected, underfunded and left poorly prepared despite growing security risks in Europe.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] This criticism became more prominent after the invasion of Ukraine, when Germany's defence policy came under closer domestic and international scrutiny.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's broader approach to Russia was associated with *Wandel durch Handel*, the policy of pursuing close economic ties with authoritarian governments in the expectation that trade would encourage moderation or democratisation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] After Russia's invasion of Ukraine, this policy came under intense criticism, with Merkel receiving much of the blame for Germany's strategic dependency on Moscow.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy also criticised Merkel and former French president Nicolas Sarkozy for blocking Ukraine's NATO aspirations in 2008.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel defended the decision, arguing that Ukraine would have been militarily weaker had the conflict escalated earlier.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's energy policy was criticised for combining the phase-out of nuclear power with continued dependence on fossil fuel imports, including Russian gas.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that the nuclear phase-out reduced reliable domestic low-carbon power generation and increased Germany's exposure to imported energy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism became stronger during the 2021–2022 global energy crisis, when rising energy prices and supply concerns placed Germany's energy strategy under scrutiny.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents also criticised the interaction between Germany's nuclear exit, coal phase-out and climate policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] While Merkel's governments supported the European Green Deal and long-term decarbonisation, critics argued that the transition was poorly sequenced and left Germany vulnerable to both energy insecurity and high prices.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised in debates over the wider direction of the European Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Some politicians and commentators argued that German-led austerity during the eurozone crisis, the handling of the migration crisis and the reluctance of EU leaders to accommodate British concerns contributed to anti-EU sentiment.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In debates over Brexit, critics claimed that continental Europe, including Germany under Merkel, bore part of the responsibility for the political climate that led to the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] This argument was particularly common among Eurosceptic and right-wing critics, who linked the eurozone and migration crises to declining trust in EU institutions.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Studies of far-right discourse in Germany have noted that AfD politicians sometimes portrayed Merkel's refugee policy as contributing to Brexit.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Scholars generally treat Brexit as the result of multiple domestic and European factors, but critics of Merkel have continued to cite it as part of a broader backlash against the EU during her period of leadership.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was widely described as the *de facto* leader of the European Union throughout her tenure as Chancellor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] She was named the world's second most powerful person by *Forbes* magazine in 2012 and 2015, following Barack Obama and Vladimir Putin respectively, the highest ranking ever achieved by a woman.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] On 26 March 2014, Merkel became the longest-serving incumbent head of government in the European Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In December 2015, Merkel was named as *Time* magazine's Person of the Year, with the magazine's cover declaring her to be the "Chancellor of the Free World".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In 2018, Merkel was named the most powerful woman in the world for a record fourteenth time by *Forbes*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Following the election of Donald Trump to the US presidency in 2016, Merkel was described by *The New York Times* as "the Liberal West's Last Defender", and as the "leader of the free world" by a number of commentators, including Hillary Clinton.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In a 2018 survey, Merkel was found to be the most widely respected world leader.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] *The Atlantic* described her in 2019 as "the world's most successful living politician, on the basis of both achievement and longevity".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Harvard University President Larry Bacow described her as "one of the most widely admired and broadly influential statespeople of our time".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Critics have argued that Merkel's policymaking during the 2015 migrant crisis has damaged the integrity of the EU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Some have also commented that Germany's failure to meet financial commitments to NATO, Merkel's blocking of the accession of Ukraine to NATO in 2008, and the abolishment of conscription have together weakened the positions of Germany and Europe following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has been described as having significantly shaped the political landscape of Germany, particularly the perceptions of those who grew up during her chancellorship; this demographic group has been referred to *Merkelkinder* (transl. children of Merkel).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] As a woman who is a politician from a centre-right party and also a scientist, Merkel has been compared by many in the English-language press to 20th-century British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Thatcher also had a science degree from Oxford University in chemistry.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Some have referred to her as "Iron Lady", "Iron Girl", and even "The Iron Frau", all alluding to Thatcher, whose nickname was "The Iron Lady".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Political commentators have debated the precise extent to which their agendas are similar.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Later in her tenure, Merkel acquired the nickname *"Mutti"* (a German familiar form of "mother").
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] She has also been called the "Iron Chancellor", in reference to Otto von Bismarck.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In 1977, at the age of 23, Merkel, then Angela Kasner, married physics student Ulrich Merkel (born 1953) and took his surname.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Her second and current husband is quantum chemist and professor Joachim Sauer, who has largely avoided media attention during and after Merkel's political career.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] They first met in 1981 and married in 1998.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has no children, but Sauer has two adult sons from a previous marriage.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Having grown up in East Germany, Merkel learned Russian at school.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] She was able to speak informally to Vladimir Putin in Russian but conducted diplomatic dialogue through an interpreter.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] She rarely spoke English in public, but delivered a small section of an address to the British Parliament in English in 2014.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel is a fervent football fan and was known to listen to games while in the Bundestag and to attend games of the national team in her official capacity, including Germany's 1–0 victory against Argentina in the 2014 World Cup Final.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has stated that her favorite film is *The Legend of Paul and Paula*, an East German movie released in 1973.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has a fear of dogs, which developed after she was attacked by one in 1995.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Vladimir Putin brought in his Labrador Retriever during a press conference in 2007.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Putin claims he did not mean to scare her, though Merkel later observed, "I understand why he has to do this – to prove he's a man. ...
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Since 2017, Merkel has occasionally been seen shaking visibly on several public occasions, recovering shortly afterwards.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] After one such occasion, she attributed the shaking to dehydration, saying that she felt better after a drink of water.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In September 2021, after evading the question for most of her career, Merkel said that she considered herself a feminist.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The statement came in a conference along with Nigerian writer and feminist Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Since her retirement, Merkel has commented on the Russo-Ukrainian war, but has otherwise limited her involvement in political matters.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] She has instead focused on travelling, attending only "feel-good events" (*Wohlfühltermine*) in a private capacity.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] President Donald Trump, according to *Politico*, citing a forthcoming book by Jonathan Karl.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] The EKBO is a member of the Union of Protestant Churches in the EKD.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Before the 2004 merger of the Evangelical Church in Berlin-Brandenburg and the Evangelical Church in Silesian Upper Lusatia, Merkel belonged to the former.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In 2012, Merkel said, regarding her faith: "I am a member of the Protestant Church.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] I believe in God and religion is also my constant companion, and has been for the whole of my life.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] We as Christians should above all not be afraid of standing up for our beliefs." She also publicly declared that Germany suffers not from "too much Islam" but "too little Christianity".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Since 1991, Merkel has sat annually for sitting and standing portraits by, and interview with, Herlinde Koelbl.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was portrayed by Swiss actress Anna Katarina in the 2012 political satire film *The Dictator*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel features as a main character in two of the three plays that make up the Europeans Trilogy (*Bruges*, *Antwerp*, and *Tervuren*) by Paris-based UK playwright Nick Awde: *Bruges* (2014) and *Tervuren* (2016).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] A character named Merkel, accompanied by a sidekick called Schäuble, also appears as the sinister female henchman in Michael Paraskos's novel *In Search of Sixpence*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] On the American sketch-comedy series *Saturday Night Live*, Merkel has been parodied by Kate McKinnon.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] On the British sketch-comedy *Tracey Ullman's Show*, comedian Tracey Ullman has parodied Merkel to international acclaim.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In 2016, a documentary film *Angela Merkel – The Unexpected* was produced by Broadview TV and MDR in collaboration with Arte and Das Erste.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] In 2024, a German TV show called 'Miss Merkel' reimagined her as a detective.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/angela-merkel-p02] It is based on the bestselling novels by German writer David Safier and is a comedy that was a hit in Germany and then shown on public broadcaster RAI, dubbed into Italian.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In February 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer announced that she would resign her position as CDU leader later in the year and would not put herself forward as a candidate for chancellor for the 2021 federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was succeeded by Armin Laschet at the January 2021 CDU leadership election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer previously served as secretary general of the party and as Minister President of Saarland from 2011 to 2018, the first woman to lead the Government of Saarland and fourth woman to head a German state government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is regarded as socially conservative, but on the CDU's left wing in economic policy and has been described as a centrist.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is an active Catholic and has served on the Central Committee of German Catholics.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is the second woman to hold the office of German defence minister.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was succeeded by Christine Lambrecht.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2021 she proposed for the use of nuclear weapons against Russia via a First-Strike capability as a deterrence against any "provocation" or aggression.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She renounced her Bundestag mandate and retired from politics after the 2021 federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Annegret Kramp was born on 9 August 1962 in Völklingen, located on the Saar River midway between Saarlouis and Saarbrücken, around 40 kilometres from Luxembourg and close to the border with France.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She grew up in the neighbouring town of Püttlingen.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Her father was a special education teacher and a headmaster.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She graduated from high school in 1982 and considered becoming a school teacher, but decided to study politics and law at the University of Trier and at Saarland University, where she earned a master's degree in 1990.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer joined the CDU while still in high school in 1981.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1984 she was elected to the district council of Püttlingen, and in 1985 became chairwoman of the city's CDU association.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 1985 to 1988 she was also a member of the regional board of the Young Union in Saarland.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 1991 to 1998 she served as a policy and planning officer for the CDU in Saarland under environment minister Klaus Töpfer.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1998, Kramp-Karrenbauer replaced Töpfer in the federal Bundestag, serving seven months before losing re-election in the SPD landslide the same year.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 1999, she was an advisor to Peter Müller, then chairman of the CDU parliamentary group in the Landtag of Saarland and later Minister-President.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] That same year she became a chairwoman of the Women's Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was elected to the Landtag of Saarland in 1999.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She served as Minister of the Interior in the government of Peter Müller; the first woman to hold that office in Germany.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She took on more responsibilities in 2004, and changed roles in 2007 following a cabinet reshuffle, becoming Minister of Education and again in 2009, becoming Minister of Labor in the so-called Jamaica coalition government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2008, she was elected chairwoman of the *Kultusministerkonferenz*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Throughout her time in state government, she also served at various times as minister responsible for women, sports, family, and culture.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the negotiations to form a coalition government following the 2009 federal election, Kramp-Karrenbauer was part of the CDU–CSU delegation in the working group on education and research policy, led by Annette Schavan and Andreas Pinkwart.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly afterwards, she ended the coalition and triggered an election, blaming the party for "dismantling itself" and arguing that the three-party coalition had lost the necessary "trust, stability, and capacity to act".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Under Kramp-Karrenbauer's leadership, the CDU won 40.7% of the vote in the 2017 state elections, up from 35.2% in 2012.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] While serving as Minister-President, Kramp-Karrenbauer, who speaks French, was also Commissioner of the Federal Republic of Germany for Cultural Affairs under the Treaty on Franco-German Cooperation between 2011 and 2014.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She continued to be a member of the German-French Friendship Group that was set up by the upper chambers of the German and French national parliaments, respectively the Bundesrat and the Senate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Furthermore, as one of the state's representatives at the federal Bundesrat, she served on the Committee on Cultural Affairs, the Committee on Foreign Affairs, and the Committee on Defence.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention to elect the president of Germany in 2012 and in 2017.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was also for a short time part of the CDU–CSU delegation's leadership team in the negotiations to form a "grand coalition" following the 2013 federal elections.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She again played a role in the negotiations to form a fourth coalition government under Chancellor Angela Merkel in 2018, leading a working group on education policy alongside Stefan Müller, Manuela Schwesig and Hubertus Heil.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As Minister-President of Saarland, Kramp-Karrenbauer promoted the French language, aiming to make the state fully bilingual in German and French and thus promote Saarland as a bicultural European region similar to neighbouring Luxembourg.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] While Saarland had rejoined Germany five years before Kramp-Karrenbauer's birth when a majority voted against becoming an independent state, it has a long history of association with France dating back to the late 18th century.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In February 2018, Merkel nominated Kramp-Karrenbauer as the new secretary general of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was confirmed at the CDU party conference on 26 February, securing 98.87% of the vote.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As secretary general, she managed the party and oversaw its election campaigns.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She also embarked on a major listening tour of the country, holding more than 40 meetings with local CDU associations and working on a new political manifesto for the party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2018, following bad results for the CDU/CSU in state elections in Bavaria and Hesse, Chancellor Merkel announced she would not stand for re-election as party leader in the CDU convention at the end of the year, triggering a leadership election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Former Bundestag leader of the CDU and businessman Friedrich Merz jumped into the race immediately while Health Minister Jens Spahn and Kramp-Karrenbauer announced their bids shortly after.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was perceived to be Merkel's chosen heir and a continuation of her style and centrist ideology while Merz was an old rival from Merkel's early days as party leader and was very open about his intention to move the party in a more conservative direction.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Nevertheless, the Chancellor did not state her preferences.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As the vote approached, opinion polls showed that Kramp-Karrenbauer was favoured by CDU voters and the general public alike.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The contest was held on 7 December and after coming out on top in the first round, Kramp-Karrenbauer narrowly defeated Merz in a run-off, becoming the new leader of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the immediate aftermath of her election, surveys showed an increase in the CDU's vote share; however, it was short-lived.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the first months of her tenure, there were a series of gaffes and according to the press a failure to connect with voters.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In the run-up to the 2019 European Parliament election, which was seen as her first major electoral test, the CDU's campaign was embroiled by a row between the party and YouTube personality Rezo.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] It was caused by a viral YouTube video posted by Rezo in which he called out the parties of the governing Grand Coalition (CDU/CSU and SPD) and urged viewers not to vote for them.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer reacted, stating that the electoral law should be changed to prevent social media personalities like Rezo from influencing the voters' choice in the midst of a campaign.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The statement was harshly criticized as an attack on freedom of expression and damaged the image of Kramp-Karrenbauer among young people.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly afterwards, a Bloomberg report stated that Chancellor Merkel thought that her successor was not up to the job, further hindering her popularity.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The European Elections resulted in the CDU's worst national showing ever, below 30%.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] After the underwhelming result, rumors emerged that some CDU politicians planned to shun Kramp-Karrenbauer and put up another Chancellor candidate for the next Bundestag election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer announced her resignation as leader of the CDU on 10 February 2020 as a result of the 2020 Thuringian government crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] The plan was that she would resign in the summer and her successor would be elected, but this was postponed to December due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When Ursula von der Leyen was elected President of the European Commission in July 2019, Kramp-Karrenbauer succeeded her as Federal Minister of Defence in the government of Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] This was the first time that she held a position in the federal government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] For the 2021 elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer was later elected to lead the CDU campaign in Saarland.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Shortly after having been elected, she announced her decision to step down from the parliament and instead make room for Markus Uhl who had failed to secure a seat.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In mid-2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer oversaw the German military's withdrawal from Afghanistan after almost two decades.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In July 2021, she sent the frigate *Bayern* off on a seven-month voyage that will take it to Australia, Japan, South Korea and Vietnam, making it the first German warship to pass through the South China Sea since 2002.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] During her time in office, Kramp-Karrenbauer publicly apologized to soldiers who for decades faced discrimination, discharge or convictions on the basis of their sexual orientation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2021, she successfully introduced legislation to rehabilitate those soldiers.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer disbanded a company of the Special Forces Command (KSK) after police seized weapons and ammunition during a raid on the property of a KSK soldier.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She later resisted calls for KSK to be disbanded altogether and instead pushed through the unit's reform.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In June 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer recalled 30 German soldiers from service at the NATO Enhanced Forward Presence in Lithuania, with ringleaders facing immediate dismissal, after an article in *Der Spiegel* accused them of making racist and anti-Semitic remarks and of sexual violence.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Also in 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer opened the Bundeswehr's first-ever Air and Space Operations Centre (ASOC) in Uedem, expanding Germany's existing space situation center into the new structure.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] During Kramp-Karrenbauer's tenure as Minister-President of Saarland, she had consistently high approval ratings in the low to mid-70's among her constituents.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She was the most popular politician in Saarland according to Infratest dimap from November 2010 until her departure as Minister-President.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer was considered one of the most popular state government leaders nationwide.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When entering federal politics, Kramp-Karrenbauer had a positive net approval rating from her election as CDU General Secretary in February 2018 until March 2019, just shortly after having been elected as Leader of the Christian Democratic Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Her nationwide popularity peaked in January 2019, when she had a net approval of +17% and was seen as second-most popular politician overall.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] There was then a sharp decline in her popularity following gaffes and electoral defeats for the Christian Democrats in several elections.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] As of February 2020, she is one of the least popular German politicians.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] From 2024 to 2025, Kramp-Karrenbauer chaired an independent expert commission convened by the Global Perspectives Initiative to develop recommendations for Germany's development policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Since 2026, Kramp-Karrenbauer has been serving as chair of the Konrad Adenauer Foundation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is perceived as a moderate or centrist Christian Democrat.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She has been described as socially conservative, but on the CDU's left wing in economic policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is regarded as more conservative than Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Nevertheless, in the German press, her often used nickname during her party leadership was "Mini-Merkel", reflecting both her size and her political views.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer opposes same sex marriage, having compared it to incest and polygamy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Amid her party's campaign for the 2013 federal elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer suggested Germany return to a top income tax rate of more than 53%, setting off a fierce debate in her party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In her view, Merkel's predecessor Gerhard Schröder had gone too far in reducing the top rate from 53% to 42% in the 1990s.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In May 2014, she was among leading members of Merkel's CDU who called for reductions to offset fiscal drag—the automatic increases in the tax-take that occur as inflation and income growth push wage-earners further into their marginal higher tax-bracket.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] When the Federal Constitutional Court ruled in favour of tax equality for same-sex couples in 2013, Kramp-Karrenbauer voiced her concerns about also granting full adoption rights for same-sex couples, stating: "The traditional family unit is the core of not only Germany but all nations".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In 2015, she caused a public controversy by arguing that "if we open up [the definition of marriage] to become a long-term responsible partnership between two adults, then other demands can't be ruled out, such as a marriage between close relatives or between more than two people".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] For the 2021 national elections, Kramp-Karrenbauer endorsed Armin Laschet as the Christian Democrats' joint candidate to succeed Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer criticised the German-supported Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline that would allow Germany to effectively double the amount of gas it imports from Russia, saying that Nord Stream 2 "is not just an economic project but a political one".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Ambassador to Germany Richard Grenell sent letters to German companies involved in the construction of Nord Stream 2, threatening CAATSA sanctions.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer has supported arms exports to Saudi Arabia, which has been waging war in Yemen and was condemned for massive human rights violations.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In late 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer proposed that the European Union should try again to reach a trade agreement with the United States after the elections.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] In October 2021, Kramp-Karrenbauer had talked about the possibility of deploying nuclear arms against Russia.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer supports stricter immigration policies.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer supported Angela Merkel's refugee policies and her decision to let migrants into Germany in 2015–2016, many fleeing wars in the Middle East, but demanded more toughness in some cases.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] At the beginning of 2016, she declared herself against a unilateral closure of German borders, since she feared a break-up of the European Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Furthermore, instead of carrying out deportations with commercial airplanes, she said it may be necessary to use their separate aircraft.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She demanded in November 2018 that after expulsion offenders must be refused re-entry for life, not only to Germany but also throughout the Schengen area, and cited the 2018 gang rape in Freiburg as an example.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] She is married to Helmut Karrenbauer, a retired mining engineer, with whom she has three children, born in 1988, 1991 and 1998; they live in the city of Püttlingen.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annegret-kramp-karrenbauer] Kramp-Karrenbauer is an avid reader and speaks French.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Throughout her political career, Schavan was widely known to be a friend and a confidante of Merkel's.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Schavan was born in Jüchen on 10 June 1955.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] From 1995 until 2005, Schavan served as State Minister of Cultural Affairs, Youth, and Sports for the German state of Baden-Württemberg in the governments of successive minister-president Erwin Teufel and Günther Oettinger.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] During this time, she oversaw school education in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] One controversy that erupted during this time was when a Muslim teacher was banned from wearing a head scarf in school, as that was interpreted as a religious symbol, while at the same time allowing Catholic nuns to wear their traditional habits.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] The argument was that the habits of nuns and monks have an official function, while a Muslim headscarf is optional.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Schavan was regarded as a possible Christian Democratic candidate for Germany's presidency in 2004, but Horst Köhler was nominated and elected instead.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In 2005, she attempted to succeed Erwin Teufel as Minister-President of Baden-Württemberg, but she was defeated by her rival Günther Oettinger in the internal elections of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Oettinger's referendum win – with 60.6 percent of the vote versus 39.4 percent for Schavan – was widely seen at the time as a defeat for Teufel, who had promoted Schavan as his preferred successor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Under the leadership of party chairwoman Angela Merkel, Schavan was re-elected vice-chairwoman of the CDU in November 2006, this time alongside minister-presidents Roland Koch, Jürgen Rüttgers and Christian Wulff.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Schavan served as Federal Minister of Education and Research from 2005 to February 2013.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Following the 2009 federal elections, she was part of the CDU/CSU team in the negotiations with the FDP on a coalition agreement.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] She led her party's delegation in the working group on education and research policy; her co-chair of the FDP was Andreas Pinkwart.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In 2010, Schavan led efforts to enlist imams educated at German universities to improve the integration of young Muslims.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Under a plan devised by the German Council of Science and Humanities, imams were to be trained at two or three German universities, in accordance with the German curriculum.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In addition to theology, the new preachers would also study education and community organizing.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In a competition, the universities of Tübingen, Münster and Osnabrück were selected for the program.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] On the occasion of the sixtieth anniversary of the diplomatic relations between Germany and India, Schavan participated in the first joint cabinet meeting of the two countries' governments in Delhi in May 2011.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In 2012, Schavan chaired the Joint Science Conference (GWK), a body which deals with all questions of research funding, science and research policy strategies and the science system that jointly affect the federal government and the 16 federal states.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Following her resignation, Schavan was succeeded by Johanna Wanka.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In 2017, Schavan was one of the candidates considered to succeed Hans-Gert Pöttering as chair of the Konrad Adenauer Foundation (KAS) until she withdrew herself from consideration; instead, the role went to Norbert Lammert.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] In April 2023, Schavan was one of the 22 personal guests at the ceremony in which Angela Merkel was decorated with the Grand Cross of the Order of Merit for special achievement by President Frank-Walter Steinmeier at Schloss Bellevue in Berlin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Amid the plagiarism scandal that led to the resignation of Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg as Minister of Defence of Germany on 1 March 2011, Schavan was quoted in *Der Spiegel* as saying that "intellectual theft is not a small thing".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Investigators found paraphrasing of secondary literature without naming the source in over 60 cases in the dissertation and thereby on 5 February 2013 revoked her doctorate degree because of "systematic and premeditated" deception.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] On 9 February 2013, it was reported that chancellor Angela Merkel had accepted Annette Schavan's resignation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Schavan continued to deny any wrongdoing and pursued a court appeal against the process by which the university had revoked her doctorate.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] On 20 March 2014 a Düsseldorf court rejected her appeal, however.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Following the death of Pope John Paul II, Schavan – then serving as deputy chairperson of the Central Committee of German Catholics, the church's lay organisation – demanded that the "we need more lively local churches, and therefore also more autonomy [from Rome] for local parishes".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] Ahead of the Christian Democrats' leadership election in 2018, Schavan publicly endorsed Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer to succeed Angela Merkel as the party's chair.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-schavan] For the 2021 national elections, Schaven endorsed Armin Laschet as the Christian Democrats' joint candidate to succeed Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In the 1998 federal election Widmann-Mauz was elected from the CDU Baden-Württemberg list, the second largest chapter of her party.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] Four years later, in 2002, she was elected directly for the constituency of Tübingen.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] She has won each re-election in this electoral district at all federal elections since.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In her first legislative term, Widmann-Mauz joined the Committee on Health.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] Between 2005 and 2009, she served as her parliamentary group's spokesperson on health policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] Since 2003, Widmann-Mauz has been serving as deputy chairwoman of the CDU Baden-Württemberg, under the leadership of successive chairmen Erwin Teufel (2003-2005), Günther Oettinger (2005-2009), Stefan Mappus (2009-2011) and Thomas Strobl (since 2011).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] On 29 October 2009 she became Parliamentary State Secretary at the Federal Ministry of Health.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In the second Merkel cabinet, she first served alongside Daniel Bahr under the leadership of Minister Philipp Rösler (2009-2011) and later under Bahr, who replaced Rösler in 2011.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In 2011, she participated in the first joint cabinet meeting between the German government and the State Council of the People's Republic of China in Berlin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] From 2012 to 2022, Widmann-Mauz was a member of the CDU's national board under the leadership of successive chairs Angela Merkel (2012-2018), Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer (2018–2021) and Armin Laschet (2021–2022).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] She co-chaired the CDU's national conventions in Karlsruhe (2015) and Essen (2016).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In the negotiations to form a third cabinet under Merkel following the 2013 federal elections, Widmann-Mauz led the working group on families, alongside Manuela Schwesig.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In the new coalition government, she again served as Parliamentary State Secretary for Health, this time under the leadership of Minister Hermann Gröhe.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] From 2015 to 2025, Widman-Mauz led the Christian Democrats’ Women's Union.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In the negotiations to form a fourth cabinet under Merkel following the 2017 federal elections, Widmann-Mauz led the working group on families, alongside Angelika Niebler and Katarina Barley.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] She was subsequently appointed Minister of State for Migration, Refugees and Integration in the Federal Chancellery under Merkel.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] Following her party's defeat in the 2021 elections, Widmann-Mauz announced her candidacy as Vice President of the Bundestag; however, the CDU/CSU parliamentary group eventually nominated Yvonne Magwas for the position.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In July 2024, Widmann-Mauz announced that she would not stand in the 2025 federal elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In 2014, Widmann-Mauz negotiated legislation requiring German companies to allot 30 percent of their non-executive board seats to women from 2016.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In June 2017, Widmann-Mauz voted against Germany's introduction of same-sex marriage.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] Ahead of the Christian Democrats’ leadership election in 2018, Widmann-Mauz publicly endorsed Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer to succeed Angela Merkel as the party's chair.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/annette-widmann-mauz] In April 2020, Widmann-Mauz co-signed – alongside around 50 other members of her parliamentary group – a letter to President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen which called on the European Union to take in children who were living in migrant camps across Greece.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet earned a law degree and worked as a journalist before and during his early political career.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 1994 he was elected to the Bundestag and in 1999 he became a Member of the European Parliament.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2005 he entered state politics in North Rhine-Westphalia as a member of the state government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2012 he became leader of the state party, and he was elected Prime Minister of the state in 2017.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His Cabinet consisted of members of his own CDU and the liberal Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In January 2021, Laschet was elected leader of the CDU, winning 52.8% of delegates votes against Friedrich Merz in the second round of the contest.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] The result of the election was certified by postal vote of the party conference's delegates with the final result announced on 22 January.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] It was confirmed on 20 April 2021 that he would be the CDU/CSU candidate for Chancellor of Germany at the 2021 German federal election, after rival Markus Söder conceded.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He was born to an observant Roman Catholic family of German-speaking Walloon origin; his father's parents were both of Belgian origin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He is married to Susanne Malangré, whom he met in a Catholic children's choir when they were children and who is a member of a prominent Aachen political family of French-speaking Walloon origin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] On 9 February 2024, he was awarded an honorary doctorate from TED University.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet is a lecturer for political science at LMU Munich.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet was born in Burtscheid, a suburb of Aachen, about three kilometres from the Belgian and Dutch borders, to parents Heinrich Laschet and Marcella née Frings; he was raised in an observant Roman Catholic family.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His father was a mining engineer at a black coal mine and later became an elementary school teacher and headmaster.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Like many others in the tri-border area the Laschets had relatives across the national boundaries, who lived in Belgium, The Netherlands, Germany and Neutral Moresnet.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet maintains close personal ties to Belgium where members of the Laschet family still live.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He attended the Pius-Gymnasium in Aachen and studied law at the University of Bonn and LMU Munich, passing the first state examination in law in 1987.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He studied journalism from 1986 to 1988.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In Munich, he became a member of K.D.St.V.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Aenania München, a Catholic student fraternity that is member of the Cartellverband.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet worked as a journalist and in the publishing industry from 1986 until 1991, among other things as Bonn correspondent for Bayerischer Rundfunk.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He later served as editor-in-chief of the Catholic newspaper *KirchenZeitung Aachen* from 1991 until 1994.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] From 1995 to 1999, while also serving as a member of parliament, he was CEO of the Catholic publishing company Einhard-Verlag, which had previously been led by his father-in-law Heinrich Malangré.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] After serving as staffer to the President of the Bundestag, Laschet became a member of the German Bundestag in the 1994 election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He was elected in the single-member constituency of Aachen I, after the incumbent Hans Stercken retired.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He was on the Committee for Economic Cooperation and Development and on the Committee for European Union Affairs.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In addition, he was part of the so-called "Pizza-Connection" (a reference to an American drug ring).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] A number of informal meeting of a group of young Bundestag Members from both the CDU and the Greens.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] This was later seen as controversial, because it solidified an image of him as a liberal/centrist member of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He lost re-election in the 1998 SPD landslide to future Health Minister Ulla Schmidt.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] As Member of the European Parliament, Laschet served on the Committee on Budgets between 1999 and 2001 and on the Committee on Foreign Affairs between 2002 and 2005.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In the latter capacity, he served as the Parliament's rapporteur on relations between the EU and the United Nations.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Under Minister President Jürgen Rüttgers in North Rhine-Westphalia, Laschet served as State Minister for Generations, Family, Women and Integration from 2005 until 2010, and as State Minister for Federal Affairs, Europe and Media from 2010.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2010, he unsuccessfully ran against Norbert Röttgen for the post of CDU chairman in the state.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] When Röttgen resigned from that office in 2012, Laschet was elected as his successor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] On 4 December 2012, he was elected as one of five deputy chairpersons of the national CDU party, serving alongside Volker Bouffier, Julia Klöckner, Thomas Strobl and Ursula von der Leyen.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet currently serves as state MP in the Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia and also chairs the CDU's state chapter (Landesverband).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] From 2014 until 2016, he was a member of the North Rhine-Westphalia Commission for Constitutional Reform, led by Rainer Bovermann.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In November 2015, Laschet visited the Zaatari refugee camp in Jordan to learn more about the plight of Syrians fleeing the violence in the ongoing Syrian civil war that erupted in 2011.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Between March 2015 and January 2016, he chaired the Robert Bosch Expert Commission to Consider a Realignment of Refugee Policy, an expert group convened by the Robert Bosch Stiftung.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In November 2016, Laschet was elected leading candidate for the North Rhine-Westphalia state elections in May 2017 which he won in what was widely considered an upset victory.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the President of Germany in 2017.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In December 2016, Laschet presided over the CDU's national convention in Essen.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet served as the 11th Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia from 2017 to 2021.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet's government was a coalition between the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] As one of his state's representatives at the Bundesrat, he serves as a member of the Federal Committee on Foreign Affairs and the Defence Committee.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He named Jens Spahn as his vice-presidential candidate, with Friedrich Merz and Norbert Röttgen as his challengers.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Polls subsequently showed that voters rated Laschet's management of the COVID-19 pandemic in Germany's most populous state poorly.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] The election of the new CDU party president, after several postponements due to the coronavirus epidemic, took place only at the two-day party congress in mid-January 2021, which was the first fully digital congress in the party's history.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] On the second day of the congress, 16 January 2021, Laschet won 38.42% of the votes in the first round and 52.79% in the second round.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He thus became the new president of the CDU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] After his defeat at the head of his party in the federal elections, he resigned from the party leadership on 7 October.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His place was taken by Merz, who finally succeeded in his third attempt, in the election of the party president on 17 December 2021.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] However, the strong intra-party divisions that were also evident in the vote could have led to a joint CDU/CSU chancellorship candidacy for Markus Söder, the president of the smaller Bavarian sister party, the CSU.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Polls conducted immediately before the party congress showed that 55 percent of voters considered Söder a good candidate for chancellor, while 80 percent of CDU/CSU supporters thought he was a good candidate, compared to only 27 percent and 32 percent respectively for Laschet.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Subsequently, following a late-night meeting of the CDU leadership in Berlin, it was announced that in a secret ballot, 77.5 percent of those present at the meeting had finally backed Laschet, compared to just 22.5 percent for Söder.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Thus, it was a foregone conclusion that Armin Laschet would be in the running to become chancellor of the CDU/CSU coalition in September 2021.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Already at the party congress in Rhineland-Palatinate in May 2021, Laschet called for the Greens to be the main political opponent in the upcoming election campaign.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He set the goal of preventing the formation of a Red–Red–Green (SPD–Left–Greens) coalition.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] As his party's candidate to succeed Merkel in the national elections, Laschet was initially seen as having made an uncertain start to his campaign and faced calls to chart a more right-wing course to win back voters disenchanted by the incumbent coalition government.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] However, the party's win in the Saxony-Anhalt elections was later interpreted as a boost to Laschet.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet presented the joint CDU/CSU election platform with Söder on 21 June 2021.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In the programme, they stated that combating the pandemic, climate change and defending prosperity and freedom are global challenges, and that their goal is to create a Germany open to the world, which strives for both modernisation and green policies.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] While visiting Erftstadt, a flood-hit town, Laschet was caught laughing on camera and came under fire later despite his apology that 'It was stupid and shouldn't have happened and I regret it'.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] This was a decisive factor in the fact that all but 7 percent of those surveyed were positive about the provincial premier's management of the flood crisis.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Following this incident, CDU/CSU suffered heavily in opinion polls and SPD took the lead.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet faced another scandal at the end of the month, when it emerged that he, like his fellow Green Party candidate for chancellor Annalena Baerbock, was facing accusations of plagiarism.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Zuwanderung als Chance*, was written in 2009 and he finally admitted his "mistake", and apologised.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In the 2021 German federal election on 26 September, Laschet had to compete for the post of Chancellor against Olaf Scholz of the SPD.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He did not contest an individual constituency.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His home constituency of Aachen I, which he had represented from 1994 to 1998 and was expected to be his constituency, swung to the Greens on election day.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Opinion poll predictions came true, with the SPD winning the most votes (25.7%), while the CDU/CSU had their worst result ever (24.1%).
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His former constituency of Aachen I, which he had represented from 1994 to 1998, swung to the Greens on election day.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Alliance 90/The Greens finished third with 14.8%, just ahead of the FDP with 11.5%, and both became the "kingmakers".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Two months later, they came together with the SDP to form a coalition and Olaf Scholz was elected chancellor.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Following the election, Laschet claimed personal responsibility for the party's loss.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] After the election, Laschet resigned as Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia on 25 October 2021 in order to resume his membership of the Bundestag.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He also resigned as the Leader of the CDU and was replaced by Friedrich Merz, who had won the leadership contest.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He remained a member of the Bundestag after being re-elected on the North Rhine-Westphalia party list and sat on multiple subcommittees.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He was nominated as the CDU's candidate for his former constituency of Aachen I in the 2025 German federal election.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Since 2025, Laschet has been serving as chairman of the German Parliament's Committee on Foreign Affairs.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet has been criticised for hesitancy in efforts to mitigate climate change.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] As Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia he claimed that the state was a "pioneer" in climate protection.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Environmental organisations have rebuked this claim.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] During his tenure, the expansion of wind power collapsed in North Rhine-Westphalia, so that only a third of the originally planned turbines were built.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His state government also allowed the phaseout of three coal-fired power plants to last until 2038.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2018, shortly after taking over as Minister President of North Rhine-Westphalia, Laschet supported the minister of the environment Christina Schulze Föcking's decision to dismantle the state's administrative department for environmental crimes.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Public broadcaster WDR reported that prior to its dismantling the department had been investigating accusations over pig farming at the farm of Schulze Föcking's family.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] On European integration, Laschet seeks to strengthen the European Union on issues such as fighting international terrorism and organized crime, as well as energy policy.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He also wants to see the President of the European Commission be elected directly by EU voters.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] During the European debt crisis, Laschet called for an "open discussion" toward a broad solution to the debt crisis, of which Eurobonds could be a part.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He argued that a Greek exit from the Eurozone could trigger undesirable upheaval in southern Europe: "(An exit) could lead to instability in a NATO member state.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Russia is standing ready with billions to help Greece in such a scenario." In October 2011, he signed George Soros' open letter calling for more European Union involvement in the single currency turmoil.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2020 alone, Laschet met with French president Emmanuel Macron three times.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Alongside Jens Spahn, Laschet was invited by Macron of France to attend the 2020 Bastille Day celebrations in Paris, in a sign of gratitude for their role in helping French citizens during the COVID-19 pandemic in France.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In an honour reserved for special guests, Macron invited Laschet into the Élysée Palace's gardens.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet was a fierce defender of Chancellor Merkel's migration policies during the European migrant crisis of 2015.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2016, Laschet dismissed proposals for a so-called burqa ban as a "phony debate" and distraction from more pressing issues.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] However, his party later adopted this policy as a core issue.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Ahead of a parliamentary vote in June 2017, Laschet expressed his opposition against Germany's introduction of same-sex marriage, going so far as to say it would be unconstitutional.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] During the 2021 German federal election Laschet gave a different position in a town hall, where he claimed he would have voted in favour of same-sex marriage.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2018, Laschet described the treehouses protesting the destruction of Hambach forest as "illegally occupied areas" and stated that RWE had the right to clear the forest.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] "The state government is there to ensure that the law that applies is enforced," he said during a talk show on German public broadcaster *WDR*.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet considers Germany to be insufficiently prepared for global political challenges.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In his view, the country lacks the will to pursue a foreign policy that is independent of other major powers such as Russia or the US.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2015, Laschet was criticised for not standing up for German interests when it was revealed that US intelligence agencies are illegally spying on German citizens and businesses.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] German experts estimate that by the year 2000, American industrial espionage was already causing annual economic losses of at least €10 billion per year due to stolen inventions and development projects – the number having likely only risen since then due to the increase of digitisation.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Despite these revelations, Laschet supported Angela Merkel's policy, which in leaked cables was revealed to be to "sit out" the pressure from the German public and Bundestag.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet is considered by some critics as taking a soft stance on the government of President Vladimir Putin.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet has voiced support for Nord Stream 2 and for a closer relationship with China and is against excluding Huawei from Germany's 5G network.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] However, Germany's Federal Office for Information Security has supported Laschet's position, saying that comprehensive investigations into Huawei's hardware and software have produced no evidence of wrongdoing and that an exclusion is unjustified.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Barkin further argues that Laschet has also been against "demonizing" Putin for the Russian annexation of Crimea.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] At the same time, Laschet said that Germany should increase military spending and take on a greater share of military burdens within NATO.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] He argued that the Bundeswehr should take on more responsibility in Africa, around the Mediterranean and in Mali.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2018, Laschet cancelled his appearances at the Ruhrtriennale arts and music festival due to the festival allowing supporters of the BDS movement to perform.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2013, Laschet criticised Foreign Minister Guido Westerwelle's support for rebels in the civil war in Syria: "It is absurd that the same people we are fighting in Mali are being supported in Syria.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] It is the terrorist groups al-Nusra and al-Qaida, financed from Qatar and Saudi Arabia, who are introducing Sharia courts and fighting Syria's religious diversity".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In 2013, Laschet also criticised Westerwelle's demand to release former President Mohammed Mursi after the coup in Egypt in 2013, as minorities and Christians in particular had suffered under Mursi.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet described the chaotic withdrawal of Western troops from Afghanistan and Fall of Kabul to the Taliban in August 2021 as the "biggest debacle that NATO has suffered since its founding".
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] In November 2023, Laschet criticised the German federal government for not voting against United Nations General Assembly Resolution ES-10/21.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] Laschet is married to his childhood sweetheart Susanne Malangré, whom he met as a child in a Catholic children's choir led by Susanne's father, prominent business executive Heinrich Malangré; they married in 1985.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] The family resides in Aachen's Burtscheid district.
[src:2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election/armin-laschet] His son Johannes ("Joe") Laschet, who studies law, is a blogger and model, described as a fashion influencer on Instagram.
